p.note:
Top of page in brown ink: Notes by G. E. Klemming
about the original wooden covers, replaced in the 19th century. The note also mentions the horn plates that were nailed to the wooden covers and put on the inside of the new covers. Below in black ink: a note describing the new binding made in 1958 by Sven Wiklander. Bottom of page in black ink: a reference to Swarzenski (1936)
In brown ink (rubrics and initials in red), by a medieval hand: fragment of a monastic lectionary.

binding.p: Modern binding from the 19th century, rebound in 1958 by Sven Wiklander. Brown leather over wooden boards; 2 new clasps.
binding.decoNote:
On the front cover a badly damaged double framed miniature (now flattened out but formerly wrinkled, probably as a result of the fire in 1697). The miniature was covered by plexiglass in 1958 but was originally protected by a transparent horn plate fastened by strips of silver or horn, small pieces of which are now attached to the inner face of the box. This practice is mentioned by Swarzenski (1936)
. The miniature shows St. Bartholomew, holding a book in his right hand. Sanctus Bartholomeus inscribed at the top of the frame. Outer fields: at the top the busts of the apostles James and Thomas with name scrolls, at the bottom the busts of Philip the Apostle with a name scroll and unidentified apostle (scroll probably lost); along the sides quatrefoils in a double row of lozenges. .

history.origin:
Germany , 13th century The litany of saints mentions e.g. St. Willehad, bishop of Bremen . However, his feast day (8 November) is not noted in the Calendar. Among saints mentioned in the Calendar are St Godehard of Hildesheim 5 May, St Germanus of Auxerre 31 July; St. Willibrord 7 November. The Calendar could suggest an origin in Lower Saxony, with mentions of e.g. St Suitbert (8 May), Sts Cantius, Cantianus and Cantanilla (31 May), Margaret the Virgin (13 July), cf. Kroos (1964)
. Swarzenski suggests a Franconian origin due to the decoration and binding but the liturgical evidence, such as the calendar, the series of the responsories and the readings of the Office of the Dead suggest otherwise.
history.provenance: The words S. Olaui on , probably a later addition, could suggest a Scandinavian ownership in the Middle Ages. Current signum, A 30, first established in Helin’s catalogue from the 1720s (U 91:2:2). Also mentioned in the following catalogues and inventories: U 90:4, p. 48, 135. Liber precum in membr. Latine.

decoDesc.p: The manuscript is decorated throughout. The embellishments around some of the initials may have been added by a later hand. For further description see also Lindqvist Sandgren.
decoDesc.decoNote:
